The paper focuses on using deep convolutional neural networks (D-CNNs) for human action recognition from skeletal data, which is a computer vision problem. Therefore, cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes a novel deep learning architecture based on ResNets, which is a type of neural network architecture, indicating that it could also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper deals with motion capture data, which is a multimedia topic, suggesting that it could also belong to cs.MM (Multimedia) sub-category. Finally, the paper uses deep learning techniques, which could also place it in the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category.
